#chapter(17, "An unusual karaoke session")[
  And thus, Narumi Mona entered the karaoke booth.

  She never had the chance to do karaoke in middle school, since she did not
  get too close with anyone to be invited over. Another reason was that she knew
  nothing about pop culture and their songs, so she could not sing anything that
  any high schooler would know of.

  Don't get it wrong. She loved her fair share of idol music, but that could not
  be further than what young people actually listened to. Sometimes she
  overheard her classmates talking about a song title that she knew. In such
  cases, it either went one or two ways.

  The first, which was also the more likely one, was that the song
  _coincidentally_ shared the same title as an idol song Mona knew. Her ears
  perked up in anticipation, only to drooped in disappointment, like a pet dog
  that mistook the neighbor coming home for her owner. To be honest, expecting
  them to talk about the "First Love" performed in an underground idol garage
  over the "First Love~" that was just been played live in the Budoukan
  yesterday was really unreasonable of her.

  The second case, which did occur time to time, was when she knew the song her
  classmates were talking about, but through an idol cover. So despite both she
  and them were thinking of the same songs, their impressions of the song could
  not be further apart. That's right, Mona. They were not talking about the
  "heavenly magnificent" dance moves of Miyutan, but the new plagiarized
  accusations around the original artist.

  In either case, Mona would not be able to join in the conversation.

  Mona sighed. Since this was a karaoke session, she would undoubtedly have to
  sing. If the whole "Narumi Sena" thing did not happen, maybe her friends would
  let her unscathed and treat her like a video game NPC, but well, she was the
  most popular girl in her class, so no escape it seemed.

  Today, she was invited by her friend, Kazugai Uta, to go with her friend group
  for a group karaoke. Mikoto was not joining because of club activities, so Uta
  was the only person she knew there.

  When Uta invited her over, she thought to herself, _"I can't let this chance
    go to waste!"_, and now she was walking with the group.

  She clung to the sleeve of Uta, which kind of caught her friend off guard.

  Soon enough, Mona's group entered the karaoke booth. Since it was her first
  time there, Mona took glances around the place like a curious kid exploring
  the aquarium on a first-time visit. She had heard of going to karaoke shop
  many times before, both from her older friends and her idols, but now she
  could finally truly experience it first-hand. Or first-eye, I don't know.

  An energetic boy from her group went to the stall to book a room for everyone,
  while everyone was doing small talk. Uta was happily chatting with that same
  friend from the morning, which Mona did not know the name of. Mona did have
  some questions thrown at her, but there was nothing much that could maintain a
  conversation on its own.

  She was like a statue in a museum. People looked at her in excitement and
  asked her questions, just to leave her alone when their interests ran out.
  Meanwhile, her friend Uta were still talking to that friend, with that same
  enthusiasm in both her eyes and that friend's.

  _"Uta is so amazing, she could talk to everyone like it's nothing..."_

  Mona glanced around. The boy at the cashier took out his smartphone to scan
  something, most likely the payment QR. Around her, there were a couple of
  smaller groups about to enter their respective booth. Another thing that
  caught her eyes was the juice dispenser, which Mona had seen before in fast
  food restaurants, but it seemed like this one was self-served. Next to it was
  a shelf containing all sorts of silly attachments, from animal ears to colored
  wigs.

  _"I like the cat ear thing, but everyone would probably think that it's too
    childish."_

  Other than the classic cat and dog ears, there were animal ears of different
  animals, too. There were quite a lot of horse ears, which seemed to originate
  // CONG TY DEN CONG TY DEN CONG TY TOI NHU DEM????
  from that gacha game about horse racing. Mona did not play that game, but some
  idols she knew had videos of them playing it.

  Her focus switch back to the group. It seemed that the boy has finished
  booking and returned, so everyone started moving. The group, one by one,
  walked through the narrow stairway to the second floor, where all of the
  booths resided at.

  Mona was following right after Uta, hence being the last person in the line. After
  navigating through the second floor hall, the group finally arrived at the
  karaoke room, where they would spend the next three hours at. Everyone quickly
  got down to their respective seats, and of course, Mona took the seat right
  next to Uta, her guardian angel for today.

  Now that Mona had noticed it, there were quite a lot of boys in the group,
  which was a rare sight for her.
  To Mona, seeing girls was already a rare enough occasion, and
  since she usually had no business with the other gender, she was not used to
  hanging around boys at all. There were a couple of boys in the crowd
  surrounding her in the past few days, but honestly, the most she could
  remember was them asking for a signature from her sister and nothing more.

  Mona took a quick look around. The wall was full of soundproof foam, with the
  colorful lights from the ceiling that really lighten up the mood. The low
  lounge table had some snacks prepared on it, but not quite enough for the
  whole group. The singing platform was located on a side of the room, right
  next to the entrance door. Though the TV screen was quite smaller than Mona's
  trusty friend "Mr. TV" at home, one would stand right next to it when singing,
  so there should be no problem reading the lyrics from it.

  Everyone settled down, but no one had the intention of choosing a song, let
  alone singing. A boy took the menu, seemingly intending to call for more
  snacks. A group of three decided to leave the room the exact moment they just
  went in to get some drinks for everyone. The remaining sat down comfortably
  and began chatting about random stuff.

  It took a while for things to settle down. Yet, no one had the intention to
  sing first.

  Well, except a person, that was.

  "I guess I'm gonna sing first, then."

  Uta's sudden standing up motion startled Mona. The girl glanced at her friend,
  whose voice disrupted the ongoing whispers within the group. _"So cool, she's
    like a natural leader"_, Mona thought. Ever since when, she had taken the
  controller tablet and enqueued her song on the list.

  Uta went to the singing platform, leaving the controller tablet slightly
  hanging on the table. Out of curiosity, Mona leaned forwards to know what song
  her friend was about to sing, even though the song title was already displayed
  on the TV screen. She had decided on some titles she could be singing when it
  was her turn, but she still felt a sense of nervousness and unease. Mona
  wanted to see what her friend chose. As a reference.

  // we know what this is, right?
  "Hmm... _Your Voice, Melting in the Night_ by Akatsuki, if I'm not reading
  that wrong... Haven't heard of this song before."

  Mona looked the song up on the Internet. _"Just 100,000 views? This song is
    really not too popular, isn't it?"_ She expected Uta to choose a song that was
  more mainstream, as it would fit her more, so she was kind of surprised by her
  friend's selection.

  She scrolled down the comment section of the song to see quite
  a lot of praises, surprisingly more than what a 100,000 views music video
  would regularly get. The top comment was some nerd even pointed out that it
  was "one of the greatest J-Pop song" they have ever heard, with about 20
  replies agreeing while asking "why is this song not more well-known".

  _"This does look similar to a hidden gem, if I'm not mistaken..."_

  Mona did see this kind of unusual engagement in her idols' videos, too. In the
  idol world, there were quite a lot of talented idols which unfortunately was
  not as mainstream as their counterparts, and only the most dedicated idol
  otaku would know about them. They were often considered "hidden gems" of
  idol culture, stars that only the most dedicated fans would know. Even so,
  Mona had never seen such a comment section with this much appreciation for the
  original video.

  So, by the looks of things, this might make sense, actually. A girl like Uta,
  with an enormous amount of knowledge about pop culture, would pick something
  like this as a way to prove herself. "I'm not the kind of girl that would pick
  something that is just numbers. I will show you what Kazugai Uta is truly made
  of!", something like that.

  Then, the music started.

  A cheerful tune, sounded like a mix of jingle and piano sounds, with an
  animated MV playing on the TV. All of them seemed to even highlight the cuteness
  of Uta better, bathing her in colorful lights.

  // ABSOLUTE FUCKING ESCAPE
  "These moments of fleeting love... I can't get enough of it!"

  It was a voice that Mona had never heard from her friend. A voice so girly,
  yet strong, yet lovely, yet dreamy.

  _"As if... she was an idol."_

  Uta's voice echoed throughout the room, much to the enjoyment of the whole
  group. For the entire time, Mona could not leave her eyes off of her friend,
  who was beautifully shining like an idol. The colorful MV and lighting made
  her friend sparkled brighter, which made Mona realized about the true purpose
  of such decorations and how thoughtful her song choice were.

  When the first chorus ended, leading to the first instrumental break of the
  song, Mona slightly shifted her focus on the animated music video on the TV
  screen. It was well-animated, but totally not the kind of "PikPoky" dances
  that would go viral on the Internet. The MV looked like it was telling a story
  of a salarywoman in an abusive workplace. Not sure how all of that related to the
  diabetically sweet tune of the song, though. Mona would have thought the song
  was about something like teenage love, for example.

  The four minutes of the song went by in an instant. The music stopped, and
  what's left was only a brief moment of pure silence, before a round of grand
  applause for the seemingly flawless performance. It seemed that everyone else
  was flabbergasted by the sheer display of Uta's talents. Even Mona was loudly
  clapping her hand, too.

  "Amazing!" A girl yelled from the cheering crowd, "I almost teared up!"

  "Hehe... It's nothing, really."

  Uta beamed back with a bright smile, which seemed to make the boys' heart
  skipped a beat. Heck, even Mona's heart felt the same emotion, too.

  "Well, continuing Kazugai-san's otherworldly performance, I guess I'm gonna go
  next." The girl who Uta was talking to earlier stood up after finished picking
  her song on the controller
  tablet. She came to the mini-stage to receive the microphone from Uta's hand,
  before the music to the next song started.

  "Don't blame me if I can not match Uta's quality, guys!"

  The girl grinned to the audience.

  "No problem! You just have to be half as good as her! That's enough!" A boy
  playfully cheered, "Honestly, I don't think you would be able to match that."

  "Nagi-kun! How rude of you!" The girl angrily remarked, then announced to
  everyone, "Just you see, I will blow all of your expectations away!"

  "I would like to see you try, bleh."

  The group erupted in to laughters. It seemed that these two went way back. Mona
  even suspected that they had something for each other, too.

  Once Uta got back to her seat, Mona could finally gather the courage she
  needed to ask her friend for a favor. She waited a bit for her friend to
  settle down, before raising her voice,

  "Uhmm- Uta, can you help me a bit here?"

  "Sure, what's it?"

  "Since I only know idol songs, I'm not sure what to sing when my turn comes...
  You know any idol songs that would be popular with everyone? Like idol covers
  for example?"

  Mona did have a list of potential songs she could sing, but she was not really
  sure which among them would be a good pick. Seeing how perfect her friend was,
  she finally decided to ask for help from Uta instead.

  "Hmm-, That's a bit tricky..." Uta remarked.

  "I'm sorry if it's too much of a request!" Mona clasped her hands, "Well,
  maybe can 'Your Reason' be a good fit?"

  "That song was cancelled on Mitter a month ago, so I don't think..." Uta tried
  to keep a straight face, but slip out her inner disappointment.

  "Eh! I'm sorry, erm- let me see!" Mona scrambled with the controller tablet,
  "What about 'StartEven'?"

  "The original artist was accused of murder two months ago..." Uta no longer
  could hide her emotions.

  "Wha-? Wait is there any Miyutan song without any major controversies?"

  "Miyutan? Don't you know she exclusively cover these kinds of controversial
  stuff?"

  "Huh- really?"

  "Yeah. That's right. You didn't see people trashtalking her because of it?"

  "I thought those were just toxic antis... so I blocked them."

  Uta pulled the tablet over for her helpless friend. Most of the idol songs Mona
  knew was not even available, so she could not sing them even if she wanted to.
  Though, in the first place, she did not want to anyway, as that would
  instantly out her as a creepy idol nerd.

  "How about this? You think you can sing this?" Uta, having finally found a
  song suitable for her friend, pointed on the song title.

  "Hmm- maybe this could work... But is the original song really that popular?"

  "Yeah, the last time I've checked, it got about 300 million views or something."

  "300 millions? Is it that great?"

  "I mean yeah, it's pretty popular overseas too."

  300 millions views for a J-Pop song was a number far beyond Mona's imagination.
  The highest numbers for an idol MV was just something above 1 million, so
  orders of magnitude above that was truly unimaginable for her.

  "You wanted to sing this after Rika?"

  _"Oh, so this girl is Rika? Noted! I've been calling her 'Pink-Blonde normie'
    for way too long, after all."_

  "Uhm- I think I can." Mona replied.

  "Are you sure? Like do you need some time to compose yourself up first?" Uta
  tried to give her friend some preparation, "I know public gathering can be hard
  for you, so don't force yourself."

  Mona lightly nodded. "Well, if you say so..." Uta nervously enqueued the song
  for her friend, before giving her a pat on the back,

  "Well, anyway, you got this!"

  "Thanks..."

  The two finally switched their attention back to the mini karaoke stage. The
  song was just entering the third chorus, with an explosive and catchy tune.
  Even though the girl, apparently named Rika, did not have as great of a voice
  as Uta, she was still able to gather the attention of the crowd, and her voice
  was still burning with passion. This song was a punk rock song, so it fit her
  really well.

  Soon enough, the song ended, and it was Mona's turn to sing. Mona, seeing her
  song gone from the queue to the Now Playing box, promptly stood up like a
  robot to prepare for her performance.

  "Oh! It's Narumi-san's turn." Rika handed the microphone to the nervous Mona.

  "Sena-san has a really great voice, so I'm looking forward to this!"

  "Can you stop including Narumi Sena into this please, Narumi-san must be
  sooooo--- tired of living in her own sister's shadow..."

  It seemed that everyone in the group was able to get along with each other
  now, to the point that they could give each others some silly banters. The
  mood from earlier seemed to completely melt away after just two performances.

  Though, most of the group seemed to not pay much attention to Mona, except
  for one girl.

  "Come on, Mona! You got this!"

  Uta's cheering voice miraculously reached her friend, which seemed to give
  Mona the final push she needed.

  Mona held the microphone close to her mouth. It would be unhygenic to keep it
  too close, but she had to compensate for her quiet voice. As the music was
  starting, Mona made the last preparation for the coming first verse.

  Then, she raised her voice to sing.

  Initially, her voice was somewhat low, even though it was already magnified by
  the microphone, but this situation gradually improved as Mona gained quite
  some confidence.

  With this increase in volume, Mona gradually let the microphone away from her
  mouth. This made her feel more comfortable when singing, and as a result, her
  singing became much clearer, too.

  The final chorus came and went. The song finally ended, Mona returned to her
  seat after a final round of applause. It seemed like she was getting fewer
  praises than the first two, which made her feel a little bit down.

  "Good job, Mona!" Uta gave Mona her support, "That's pretty good for a first
  time!"

  Mona gave her friend a smile, before noticing a peticularity in her friend's
  encouragement.

  "Thanks... But how did you know it's my first time?" Mona replied, worrily
  asked if she slipped out something embarrassing.

  "I mean, you do be staring at various things at the lobby, I guess."

  _"Aargh!"_ Mona screamed from the imaginary lungs in her mind. She had let
  people see that she was an old-fashioned girl who never entered any karaoke
  booth. How will she ever recover from this...

  From the outside, on the other hand, she tried to brush things off with a
  faint smile.

  Even so, this karaoke session with Uta had truly made her appreciate her
  friend even more. Not only was she a natural leader, but she was also very
  thoughtful when it comes to her friends. It had been just two days since they
  first met, but Mona felt she was forever indebt to her friend.

  Though Mona had said thanks to Uta a couple of times by now, there was still
  that urge in her to say those words again and again.

  _"Uta, I wanted to say this, but I could never find the time to. Even though
    you came to hate me, I still wanted to say it. From the deepest corners of my
    heart, thank you so much for what you have done for me. Even though it was
    brief, thank you for making me your friend."_

  Of course, her timidity would not let her do so easily.
]
